In this section, we describe the information model for implicit contextual integrity, which is used by an IAA (further detailed in Section 4) to assist its user, denoted by α, in sharing information in the OSN.
The information model considers a set of users U = {α, u1, ..., un} who are members of and communicate in an OSN. Information exchanged among users is formalised as messages denoted by tuples 〈g,R, T, S〉; where g ∈ U is the sender user, R ⊆ U is the set formed by the receiver users, and T and S represent the information that is sent. In general, messages represent any exchange of information in an OSN, where this information may be photos, comments, private messages, and so on. Let T = {t1, ..., tm} be a set of key topics or categories that can be discussed in messages. Then, T ⊆ T is the set of topics discussed in a message, and S ⊆ U are the users tagged (i.e., associated) in this message. Informally, we define a context in our problem as a group of users who interact through a specific OSN. Formally, a context C is a set of users (C ⊆ U). We denote by C = {C1, . . . , Cl} the set of contexts in which user α interacts with other users. We denote by Cβ the set of contexts that α and β share:
Cβ = {Ci|∀Ci ∈ C : β ∈ Ci}
